2026-04-21 01:32:37 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['cable connections between power supply module and control module'] hypothesis_explanation='The power‑supply module’s outputs are cross‑wired into the control module: PSU (+) is connected to the control module’s internal 0 V node and PSU (−) to the control module’s internal 12 V node. This exactly matches the intended trigger condition for the red “inverted cables” LED in the control module, which is lit. The downstream connections from the control module to the load module preserve the control module’s internal polarity, so the load sees its terminals inverted with respect to the actual 12 V source. The diode in series with the load lamp therefore blocks current, preventing both the main lamp and the internal lamp indicator from lighting, even when the switch is closed. The modules themselves appear functional; the fault is the mis‑wired polarity between the power supply module and the control module. Correcting this connection (PSU + to control +, PSU – to control –) should extinguish the red LED and allow the lamp to operate normally when the switch is turned on.'
